data: There was no Nonconformist church in the Caterham area until the Soper family founded one in 1863. Temporary premises were replaced by a chapel from 1865, and the present large building (with a prominent clock tower) was built for £6,000 and opened on 6 April 1875. Lecture rooms and a school were subsequently built as well.
St Peter and St Paul's Church

Although Claridge House is primarily a Quaker healing centre and spiritual retreat, public meetings for worship take place every Sunday as part of the West Weald Area Meeting, a group of eight Friends Meeting Houses in the Surrey and West Sussex area.
A Baptist chapel has existed in Godstone since 1882, but the present building (in the Tyler's Green area of the village) was registered for marriages in July 1940.
St Peter and St Paul's Church
St Peter and St Paul's Church
First Church of Christ, Scientist, Oxted
This Evangelical church has its church centre and administrative office at this town-centre location. Worship also takes place at a school.

A "neat little chapel" opened on 5 June 1811 in Oxted has been identified as being on Beadles Lane in the Old Oxted part of the town, although this may have been associated with the Surrey Congregational Mission. The present building on this lane is used by the Open Brethren.
This meeting house occupies part of a house on East Hill Road. It is one of eight Quaker meetings in the West Weald Area group, which covers parts of Surrey and West Sussex.
Church of the Peace of God
This had its origins in a school chapel—a combined building serving both purposes. It was originally served from the main parish church at Godstone.

This small church was originally a mission room in the parish of Limpsfield; although constituted as a full church in 1930, it remains within Limpsfield parish. A mid-19th-century rector of the parish church paid for the building to be constructed in this isolated area. Part of the church was turned into a house in 1976.
Originally registered under the name Whyteleafe United Free Church, this building was certified for marriages in April 1935.

data: Six months on and Victoria's getting used to life with Patrick, but everything changes. Nolan is now free from jail, and he vows to stay away from hacking and computers for the near future. The Initiative is revealed to have been exposed and dismantled, due to Nolan's failsafe in Carrion. Ashley is sent packing from the Hamptons for good, as Emily blackmails her into leaving with the help of Victoria. Charlotte returns from her European vacation after coping with the losses of Declan and their unborn child. Charlotte threatens Patrick, warning him to leave before he gets sucked in to their mother's evil lifestyle. Patrick leaves, and Charlotte moves out of Grayson Manor to get away from her mother. Jack returns to Montauk and reunites with Emily. He tells her that he understands why she lied, and they share a kiss. Afterward, Jack reveals that he does not have romantic feelings for Emily. He will keep her secret, but he wants her to stay away from him and Carl. At Emily's Memorial Day party, Conrad is poisoned by Emily, with the help of Nolan, and he falls ill during the reveal of his gubernatorial portrait. Emily hacks the hospital's computer files to make Conrad believe that he has Huntington's disease. Daniel also reconnects with an old friend from France, Margaux LeMarchal, the daughter of Pascal LeMarchal, a wealthy French man. After learning Emily's latest plot, Jack tells her to finish her revenge by the end of the summer and leave or else he will reveal her true identity. In response, Emily decides to set a wedding date of August 8. The two 8's in the date symbolize the double infinity symbol that Emily has tattooed on her wrist for her father. The episode ends with the return of Aiden, who wants to team up with Victoria to take down Emily, as Emily tells Nolan that she is planning "the wedding of the century".

Six months on and Victoria's getting used to life with Patrick, but everything changes. Nolan is now free from jail, and he vows to stay away from hacking and computers for the near future. The Initiative is revealed to have been exposed and dismantled, due to Nolan's failsafe in Carrion. Ashley is sent packing from the Hamptons for good, as Emily blackmails her into leaving with the help of Victoria. Charlotte returns from her European vacation after coping with the losses of Declan and their unborn child. Charlotte threatens Patrick, warning him to leave before he gets sucked in to their mother's evil lifestyle. Patrick leaves, and Charlotte moves out of Grayson Manor to get away from her mother. Jack returns to Montauk and reunites with Emily. He tells her that he understands why she lied, and they share a kiss. Afterward, Jack reveals that he does not have romantic feelings for Emily. He will keep her secret, but he wants her to stay away from him and Carl. At Emily's Memorial Day party, Conrad is poisoned by Emily, with the help of Nolan, and he falls ill during the reveal of his gubernatorial portrait. Emily hacks the hospital's computer files to make Conrad believe that he has Huntington's disease. Daniel also reconnects with an old friend from France, Margaux LeMarchal, the daughter of Pascal LeMarchal, a wealthy French man. After learning Emily's latest plot, Jack tells her to finish her revenge by the end of the summer and leave or else he will reveal her true identity. In response, Emily decides to set a wedding date of August 8. The two 8's in the date symbolize the double infinity symbol that Emily has tattooed on her wrist for her father. The episode ends with the return of Aiden, who wants to team up with Victoria to take down Emily, as Emily tells Nolan that she is planning "the wedding of the century".

table-1288-801.caption: June 12 event
data: As the 2108UTC EF3 tornado was north of Belmond (eight minutes before the EF3 dissipated), another tornado touched down to the east of town. This tornado remained over mostly open areas, though it knocked a weather mesonet station off the roof of the elementary school and downed a grove of trees.
A small tornado damaged the roof of a barn and downed about a dozen trees at two farmsteads.
Weak tornado caused minor damage to the roof of a barn and downed several trees.
Many trees and power poles were downed and one structure suffered minor shingle damage.
Brief, weak tornado with no damage.
A home was pushed off of its foundation, several outbuildings were damaged, and many trees were downed. One person was injured.
Brief tornado touched down at a farmstead and collapsed a barn, killing a horse. Debris was tossed about yards (m) to the southeast into a field, where the tornado dissipated.

Weak, brief tornado on the south side of town caused major roof and window damage to 13 homes and rolled a garage off of its cinder-block foundation. One house lost a portion of its roof and it was thrown over the top of a neighboring house. Several trees were downed as well.

Part of the roof was removed from an aluminum barn and the barn had four large doors blown out. Debris from this buildings caused damage to surrounding structures, most notably large dents in two grain silos. Another aluminum building suffered siding damage and one window was blown out.
Very brief tornado destroyed a barn, caused minor roof damage to a home, and downed trees before transitioning into a straight-line wind event.
A barn was destroyed, a soybean field was damaged, and several trees were downed.

A barn lost its roof and a house and a detached garage suffered significant damage. The damage to the house included being impacted by a beam from the barn. The top half of a pine tree was thrown feet (m) as well.
Very small, brief tornado downed wheat crops in a field. This tornado occurred simultaneously with the following event.
Very small, brief tornado collapsed the doors and one wall of a pole barn and blew over corn crops. This tornado occurred simultaneously with the previous event.

Two homes and a garage suffered minor roof and door damage and several trees were downed, one of which was thrown feet (m) to the northeast. Tornado was embedded in a larger area of straight-line winds.
